  "prompt": "How much money in charitable donations can a person deduct from his/her taxes before being taxed on his/her donations in the US?",
  "response": "In the United States, for the tax year 2022, individuals can generally deduct charitable donations up to 60% of their adjusted gross income (AGI) for cash contributions to public charities. For non-cash contributions like property or stock, the limit is typically 50% of AGI, though this can vary depending on the type of donation and the receiving organization.\n\nFor the 2022 tax year, due to changes from the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, taxpayers who take the standard deduction can also deduct up to $300 for single filers or $600 for married couples filing jointly for charitable donations, even without itemizing deductions.\n\nIt's important to note that tax laws can change, so it's always best to consult with a tax professional or check the latest IRS guidelines for the most current information specific to your situation.",
